PART III — NONPROFIT AND HUMANITARIAN LICENSING CONSIDERATION
=====================================================================

The Author strongly supports organizations that provide meaningful
charitable, humanitarian, and animal welfare services.

Registered nonprofit organizations that cannot comply with the
source disclosure requirements of the AGPL v3 may apply to the
Author for a no-cost Commercial License.

When evaluating such requests, the Author may consider factors such as:

  • Whether the organization directs the majority of its resources
    toward mission-related services.

  • Whether the organization maintains transparent public financial
    disclosures (such as IRS Form 990 or equivalent filings).

  • Whether the organization operates primarily for charitable
    purposes rather than private enrichment.

  • Whether the organization demonstrates meaningful humanitarian
    or animal welfare impact.

Examples of work the Author appreciates include, but are not limited to:

  • Facilitating the adoption of homeless animals into permanent homes.

  • Supporting or sponsoring no-kill animal shelters.

  • Providing direct humanitarian aid or services to vulnerable
    populations.

If the Author chooses to grant such permission, the license shall be
considered a voluntary and revocable gift of usage rights by the
Author in recognition of the organization's work.

Approval of one organization does not create precedent or entitlement
for any other organization.

The Author retains full discretion regarding whether such a gift
is granted.

The Author is particularly fond of organizations that help animals
find safe, permanent homes. While this sentiment is not a legal
requirement, it may improve your odds.

